<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-911-772  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 911 772.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Reseller News  Nov 20 1989 n342 p168(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The art of dealing out decision-support software.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Boyd, Wallace B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The decision-support software market is still maturing, yet itcould prove lucrative to resellers.andP;  The idea of using computersto support management surfaced in the early 1970s with experimentsat Massachusetts Institute of Technology as well as efforts by theInstitute of Management Sciences.andP;  Most programs were developedfrom an academic perspective, but the potential market is muchbroader.andP;  User-friendliness and convenience are key selling pointsof the software among executives.andP;  Decision-support software comesin four categories: executive information software, which is aimedat CEOs and provides information in highly summarized firm;traditional decision-support software, which is intended more forgeneral management purposes and which is relatively interactive;expert systems, which lets the computer do all thedecision-making; and groupware, raising decision-support to thegroup level.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Decision Support SystemsSoftware RetailingMarket ValueExecutive Information SystemsMarket Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>